Robert Rauschenberg (artist)
Billy Klüver. Swedish, born 1927 (engineer)
Oracle. 1965
5-part construction: sheet metal with iron, rubber tires, glass fragments, batteries, wire, electrical and electronica components, 59" high x 57" wide x 24" deep;
62" high x 57" wide x 35" deep;
71" high x 46" wide x 23 3/4" deep;
56" high x 40" wide x 23" deep;
62" high x 91" wide x 17" deep;
Leo Castelli Gallery, New York
</br>
Oracle is one of the first large-scale projects in which an artist and an engineer collaborated to construct a technically complex work. Its antecedent was one of Rauschenberg's combine-paintings of 1959, Broadcast, in which he used radios. Wishing to achieve a situation in which the relationship between object and spectator was less restricted, he conceived the idea of developing the project in three-dimensional objects. Three years of interrupted experiments with the radio system in collaboration with Klüver followed? New technical possibilities that presented themselves during the evolution of the work were incorporated into it. The progression from Rauschenberg's original "combine" idea into an increasingly advanced technology seems to indicate the direction that collaboration between artists and engineers is likely to take in the future.
The underlying theme of Oracle is openess and contact with the city. The components of the five sculptural pieces all come from New York, as does also the sound emitted by the five different radios. The five parts are self-contained and may be rearranged at will. This work is like a concentrate of the city situation, characterized by the accidental mixture of sound, mobility, freedom, and at the same time mutual interdependence.

344.text:
LIVE PROGRAMMING IN THE PEPSI PAVILION

In the Pepsi Pavilion, we are working together to give each visitor an opportunity to create his own physical, tactile experience in a lively, changing, sensuous environment. The concepts of choice, variety and involvement are carried through in the Live Programming planned for the Pavilion. For the Live Programming, individuals from many different professions will design programs and then come to the Pavilion to implement them. The Resident Programmer will interact with his programming and adjust, expand, and extend his efforts in response to the actual situation he finds at the Pavilion.

The Resident programmers will be artists, musicians, poets, composers, engineers, scientists, sportsmen, toy designers, playground equipment designers, architects, fashion designers, industrial designers, advertising people, rock groups, actors, singers. At any one time at the Pavilion, a team of three or four individuals from different areas will work together to program the day's activities. These mixed teams will provide the flexibility to correspond with the different types of audiences that will be visiting the Pavilion at different times of the day. Each Resident Programmer will spend between two and four weeks programming the Pavilion, and the individual schedules will be staggered in order to provide smooth transition between incoming and outgoing programmers.

The Resident Programmers have the whole Pavilion and its electronic equipment to work with. The electronic system, while complex and capable of great variety and versatility, is not complicated to program and use. The sound system, which is programmed by hard-wired program cards, has 16 inputs, and the outputs are 43 speakers arranged in a grid system in the mirror dome so that sounds can be moved in any desired pattern and at any desired speed. The sounds-in the hand sets from the Loop System and the lights in the hand sets can be programmed. The character of the fog and the light frame outside are also programmable elements. The spectacular optical properties of the dome — the three-dimensional images and the other reflections — can be moved, changed, and activated in space by various light sources. The movement, placement, duration and color of these lights can be programmed using a combination of punch-paper tape, other counting mechanisms, magnetic tape, or manual controls. A Control Console which can be played will be located on the floor of the Pavilion. The programmer can use pre-composed, pre-programmed material, and then combine it with on-the-spot manipulations and operations.

The atmosphere of the mirror-dome room can vary from being serene and calm, to a hubbub of activity, with movement of lights, many sounds, and rapidly-sequenced events. The Resident Programmers will determine the character of the space, the length of time of their programs, the movement of visitors, and the rhythm of performances and other events. The Pavilion with its great variety of moods and activities becomes a microcosm of Expo itself.

A Resident Programmer may want to use only the electronic system, for example:
	a program created by a sound-effects man from the film industry;
	creating entire sports environments such as a football game, car racing, horse racing using sound and lights;
	programs by composers or poets.

Some Programmers may want to include objects or props in their work such as :
	remote-controlled shapes flying in space;
	objects hanging in space;
	large objects emitting light and sound that roll or can be pushed.

Many of the Programmers will incorporate live performances and activities into their programs. The live performances can be short, take place at varying times, and be repeated several times a day. They will be very open, simple, flexible and mobile. The effect will be much like a traditional marketplace or bazaar where performers appear, activate the environment, and then leave.
Some examples are:
	Circus-type performances such as lasso and rope tricks, clowns, jugglers, magicians, tight-rope walkers, simple
	animal acts ;
	dance, such as excerpts from classical ballet, mime groups, folk dances ;
	sports, such as wrestling, ping pong, gymnastics, weight lifting, pole and ladder climbing, fencing, judo, karate;
	fashion shows, with models circulating on the floor;
	traditional Japanese folk dances and sports.

The above is a brief description of the possibilities for the daily programming of the Pavilion, which will make it an exciting place where things happen. The dome-shaped structure, mirror and sound system will transform these activities into beautiful phantasmagorical extensions of reality, mixing the real and the reflected in new levels of perception.

Special events will be held in the Pavilion. Television and film personalities, singers, rock groups, traditional Japanese theater and music, and well-known contemporary composers will be invited to perform there. Traditional Japanese performances will celebrate the richness of Japanese culture in which every province has its own art, ceremonies, sports, celebrations and performers. Well-known personalities will be asked to appear in the Pavilion and use the light and sound system to make special programs: an astronaut, Stirling Moss, Joe Namath, The Beatles, Duke Ellington, Allen Ginsberg, Dustin Hoffman, Sidney Poitier, Andy Warhol, and corresponding Japanese personalities.

Distinguished visitors to the Pavilion will be invited to operate the Control Console and create their own work in the environment. A further possibility for extending the number of people able to participate in the programming of the Pavilion is to have a duplicate Control Console in the United States, so that special programs could originate from this country.

A Board of Artistic Advisors here and in Japan will suggest appropriate people to be Resident Programmers. These individuals will be contacted and asked to submit proposals and ideas. The Board of Advisors and the core artists will choose which proposals will be used, thereby giving an overall theme, direction and style to the Pavilion. Procedures are being developed, and will be worked out during the coming months.

The Pepsi Pavilion developed out of a multi-sided collaboration directly involving many people, and Live Programming is an extension of this collaboration into the software phase of the project. The collaboration is using the new technology to create a lively, responsive human environment based on a belief in the positive relationship between the individual and technology and in the great possibilities for the individual which arise out of the interaction between them. It points the way to a technology of the future which will provide not repetition and uniformity, but choice and variety, with avenues for personal exploration, expression, and participation. The Pepsi Pavilion is an embodiment of the basic idea of Expo 70 in its celebration of the people themselves — their activities, their achievements and their aspirations.

